***brute force**
class Solution {
public:
    int maxArea(vector<int>& heights) 
    {
        int maxArea=INT_MIN;
        int n=heights.size();


        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            for(int j=i+1;j<n;j++)
            {
                int area = (j-i)*(min(heights[i],heights[j]));
                maxArea = max(maxArea,area);
            }
        }
        return maxArea;
    }
};

Generate all possible pairs of lines,
compute area using:

Area = (j - i) * min(height[i], height[j])

and keep track of the maximum area.

Time  : O(N²)
Space : O(1)


***2 pointer**

KEY OBSERVATION
-----------------------------------------

Area depends on:

1. Width
2. Smaller Height

The shorter line limits the water.

So move the shorter pointer.

Why?

Moving taller pointer can only reduce width
and won't increase the limiting height.

Use two pointers from both ends.
Calculate area and move the shorter
pointer because the shorter height
limits the water container.

Time  : O(N)
Space : O(1)

class Solution {
public:
    int maxArea(vector<int>& heights) 
    {
        int maxArea = INT_MIN;
        int n=heights.size();
        int l=0;
        int r=n-1;

        while(l<r)
        {
            int width = (r-l);
            int ht = min(heights[l],heights[r]);
            maxArea = max(maxArea,ht*width);

            if(heights[l]<=heights[r])
            {
                l++;
            }
            else
            {
                r--;
            }
        }
        return maxArea;        
    }
};
